They are limited to the scope of the control structure that created them

Example:
```
int a = 5;
for (int i = 0; i < 3; ++i)
{
  int b = 3;
  a += 1;
  b += 1;
  printf("a=%d, b=%d, i=%d\n", a, b, i);
}
```

This will print
```
a=6, b=4, i=0
a=7, b=4, i=1
a=8, b=4, i=2
```
Notice how `a` changed, but `b` stayed the same.

a new `b` was created each iteration of the loop, but `a` kept changes from pass to pass.

